<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAN AM TO SELL CONTRACT SERVICES UNIT; 
</P>
<P>
ANNOUNCEMENT FOLLOWS $115-MILLION PLANE DEAL WITH BRANIFF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT E. DALLOS, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Once-proud Pan Am Corp. said Tuesday that it is putting yet another of its 
properties up for sale in an effort to raise cash to support its money-losing 
airline operations. 
</P>
<P>
The company announced that it wants to sell its contract services division, Pan 
Am World Services. The proposed sale comes less than a week after the carrier 
announced that it was selling to Braniff for $115 million the rights to an 
order of 50 European-made A-320 twin-jet airliners. Pan Am now has a fleet of 
141 airliners. 
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, portions of Pan Am have been chipped away to raise cash. It 
sold its valuable office building in mid-town New York in 1980. It disposed of 
the Inter-Continental Hotel chain in 1981. In 1986, it sold to United Airlines 
its airline routes in the Pacific for more than $700 million. 
</P>
<P>
Pan Am World Services, which had revenue of $550 million in 1987 (the company 
has not yet reported 1988 results) and pretax profit of $23 million, provides 
management, housekeeping and technical services for government and commercial 
aerospace projects. 
</P>
<P>
For example, it provides various support services, including security, 
engineering, firefighting and logistics, at the Kennedy Space Center in 
Florida. It operates several airports, including the Westchester County Airport 
outside of New York City and the 30th Street Heliport in mid-Manhattan. It 
participates in the operation of some U.S. military bases and performs pilot 
training for the armed forces. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Commitment to Growth 
</P>
<P>
Pan Am would not say how much money it wants or expects to get for the 
subsidiary. But observers said it is worth about $150 million. Once it is sold, 
Pan Am Corp. will remain the owner only of Pan American World Airways, which 
has lost money throughout the 1980s, its New York-Boston-Washington air 
shuttle, which is making money, and a regional carrier, Pan Am Express, 
formerly Ransome Airlines, which serves 11 cities in the southeastern United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
Thomas G. Plaskett, Pan Am's chairman, said the proceeds from the sale and 
those from the recent deal with Braniff will be used "to strengthen Pan Am's 
financial and competitive position through further investment in the airline." 
These include, he said, commitments for $61 million for improvements to Pan 
Am's terminal at John F. Kennedy Airport in New York; $25 million for 
refurbishing the interiors of its airliners and $20 million for information 
systems improvements, customer service programs and a series of other related 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
"In taking this action," Plaskett added, "the board has recognized the progress 
that is being made at Pan Am and has demonstrated its commitment to the growth 
of Pan Am by providing internal sources of capital that will strengthen the 
carrier as it moves ahead with its recovery plan." 
</P>
<P>
But Edward Starkman, airline analyst with the New York investment firm of Paine 
Webber Inc., decried the move. 
</P>
<P>
"This is just what Pan Am should not do," he said. "It should not sell 
money-earning assets to fund the money-losing airline. This is not appealing to 
stockholders." 
</P>
</TEXT>
