second half and maintained it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011189-0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 4061 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 11, 1989, Wednesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part 3; Page 12; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
757 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 TEAMS STEP UP IN BASKETBALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN LYNCH, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The radically revised structure of the Southern Section basketball playoffs has 
crossed its first hurdle and little has changed since the start of the season: 
Few schools opted for upward mobility and confusion continues to reign. 
</P>
<P>
Among Valley-area teams, only Bell-Jeff and Crespi exercised their option last 
week to move to a higher division should either team qualify for the playoffs. 
Bell-Jeff, of the San Fernando Valley League, has moved from the 2-A to 2-AA. 
Crespi, of the Del Rey League, has moved from the 3-A to the 4-AA. 
</P>
<P>
The Southern Section has grouped playoff brackets this season by enrollment in 
order to align the section with the state playoff structure. Teams must either 
finish among the top 3 in their respective leagues or have a winning percentage 
of at least .500 to qualify for the playoffs. But when postseason play begins, 
league teams will head in various directions. (Please see accompanying chart.) 
</P>
<P>
The Southern Section will crown 9 champions, 3 more than last season, but 
officials admit the plan to form 9 32-team brackets was misguided. After 
grouping teams that automatically qualify for the playoffs, officials planned 
to fill out brackets with teams that played at least .500 ball. 
</P>
<P>
The 2-AA, for example, includes only 32 teams, and only 12 had .500 records or 
better through Friday's games. The 2-A has only 7 teams with records of .500 or 
better. 
</P>
<P>
Southern Section official Dean Crowley insisted that the 2-AA would remain 
separate from the 2-A. He admitted, however, that some brackets could shrink to 
as few as 16 or even 8 teams. 
</P>
<P>
Crespi Coach Paul Muff and Bell-Jeff Coach Joe Dunn said that they moved up 
because their schools traditionally play at higher levels. But Muff suggested 
that most teams opted for the status quo because of uncertainty surrounding the 
new system. 
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people are still confused and figure they might as well stay where 
they're at," Muff said. "Before, you always knew who you were going to compete 
against. Now everybody is spread around. I don't know if I like the system. I 
just want to see what happens." 
</P>
<P>
Despite shortcomings, Crowley sees signs that the new structure is meeting its 
goal by raising coaches' awareness of the state tournament. 
</P>
<P>
"We still feel it's very important to win a Southern Section championship, but 
we want to give our best teams a shot at a state tournament," he said. "If the 
state dropped the championship tournament, we'd go back to our old division 
concept. But as long as the state conducts its tournaments by enrollment, we 
want to follow to get our best schools in the tournament." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
