<HEADLINE>
<P>
FRESHMEN AT UCI ARE A CLASS APART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A national study of college freshmen shows that UC Irvine first-year students 
are more ethnically diverse than their counterparts at other U.S. colleges. The 
study also found that they are less likely than other college students to drink 
alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
UCI officials this week released results of the survey, which is made annually 
by the American Council of Education-UCLA Cooperative Institutional Research 
Program. 
</P>
<P>
"This year's UCI freshmen came from high schools and neighborhoods more 
racially diverse than their national counterparts," said Colleen Bentley-Adler, 
a UCI spokeswoman. "Thirty-four percent (of this year's UCI freshmen) said 
English was not their first language, compared with 5.6% at other universities. 
Only 47% said they came from a mostly white high school, while 62% at other 
universities did." 
</P>
<P>
Bentley-Adler said this year's freshmen survey shows how much UCI has changed 
since a 1978 analysis. 
</P>
<P>
"In 1978, the vast majority -- 67% -- of UCI freshmen were Caucasian," 
Bentley-Adler said. "Nearly 8% were black; 15% Asian; nearly 8% Chicano/Latino 
and 1% American Indian. Ten years later, 50% are Caucasian; 2.4% black; 40% 
Asian; 5.2% Chicano/Latino, and 1% American Indian." 
</P>
<P>
The survey's questions about religion also produced results showing how diverse 
UCI has become, Bentley-Adler noted. "By far there are more Buddhists at UCI -- 
6% -- than at other universities," she said. "Ten years ago, Buddhism was not 
even listed as a choice (on the annual freshman survey)." 
</P>
<P>
The 1988 survey found that UCI freshmen are academically brighter and less 
likely to drink alcoholic beverages than their counterparts nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
Bentley-Adler said that "more than 90% of the 1988 UCI freshmen class rated 
themselves in the top 10% in academic ability, compared with 77% at other 
universities." 
</P>
<P>
She said the survey also found that less than half of the 1988 UCI freshmen had 
ever drunk beer, wine or liquor, compared to nearly 70% at other campuses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
